Apple cinnamon pumpkin muffins🍎
Makes 6 muffins:
* 1.5 cups flour
* 1/2 cup sugar 
* 1.5 tsp baking powder
* 1/4 teaspoon baking soda
* 1/4teaspoon salt
* 1/4 tsp cinnamon
* 1/4 tsp nutmeg
* 1/2 can pumpkin purée 
* 1 egg
* 1 tablespoon vanilla 
* 1/4 cup butter
* 1 peeled apple, chopped
* 2 tbsp chilled butter
* 2 tbsp brown sugar
* 1/4 cup flour

INSTRUCTIONS:
1. Preheat the oven to 375°F
2. In a large bowl whisk together the flour, sugar, baking powder, baking soda, salt and spices
3. In another bowl, beat together the whole can of pumpkin with the eggs and vanilla
4. Add the wet ingredients to the dry, alternating with splashes of the butter. The batter will be very thick, this is normal!
5. Fold in the apples and portion into muffin tins
6. To make the crumble topping, use your hands to work the chilled butter in with the brown sugar and flour. Sprinkle this on top of the muffins.
7. Bake at 375°F for 30-35 minutes or until you can insert a toothpick and it comes out clean

How to reintroduce dairy🥛
As someone who grew up lactose intolerant, let me tell you it’s possible to reintroduce dairy and enjoy it!

Most of the time dairy intolerance is due to bacterial overgrowth in the intestines, intestinal permeability, and a stressed digestive system. The enzyme lactase which breaks down lactose is made in the cells that line the intestinal walls. Food additives, lots of raw greens, nuts, seeds and PUFAs can damage the intestinal walls affecting the production of lactase.

Each person is different, so it’s key to determine what type of milk or dairy will work for you. When you do add dairy back into your diet go slow and test different types of dairy. For example, some people find they can tolerate cheese but not milk Go slow and build up gradually.

Steps to reintroduce dairy:
	1.	Focus on healing your metabolism and your gut - when your metabolism is robust, your digestion is robust. Work on improving your metabolism first. 
	2.	The quality/type of the dairy - Choose milk that comes from pasture raised cows and support local farmers where possible. Avoid milk that has synthetic vitamins or additives. If you struggle with pasteurized milk try raw milk, A2, or goats milk to begin. 
	3.	GO SLOWWWW - if you are completely dairy free, and have been for awhile, take it slow. Start with one ounce/day of raw milk. Nothing else. Then reassess in a few days to a week and think about adding another ounce and maybe introduce a small amount of butter. 

CHEESE: ricotta, parmesan, and sheeps cheese are traditionally made and usually the cleanest.
YOGURT: traditional greek yogurt which is strained is best, it's also high in protein!

Mini Dutch babies if you’re in an egg ick but still looking for a high protein easy breakfast.

	•	1 cup flour
	•	1 cup milk
	•. 4 large eggs
	•	1/4 cup sugar
	•	1 tsp vanilla
	•	1/2 tsp salt
	•  2 scoops collagen
	•	6 tablespoons butter
	•	Powdered sugar or jam, for serving

	1.	Place a muffin pan on the rack, and heat to 425°F.
	2.	Place all ingredients except butter and toppings in a blender. Blend for 1 minute - it will be very liquidy. Let the batter rest for 10 minutes. Meanwhile, cut 6 tablespoons butter into 12 pieces.
	3.	Carefully remove the preheated muffin pan from the oven. Add 1 piece of butter to each well. Pour the batter into the wells, about 1/3 cup per well (don’t worry if the butter isn’t completely melted).
	4.	Bake until the Dutch babies are puffed and lightly golden brown, 12 to 15 minutes. Let cool for 1 minute before dusting with powdered sugar or filling with jam before serving.

My new obsession, beet kavas🫡

Traditionally, beet kavas has been used to support immune function, cleanse the blood, combat fatigue, allergies and digestive problems, but it’s especially powerful for your liver.

Beets contain phytonutrients called betalains as well as betaine that help detox your liver. 

Your liver is the cornerstone of your health  and plays a huge role in your hormones since it’s responsible for detoxing old hormones. 

It’s crazy easy to make too!

	•	1 beet, roughly chopped
	•	4 cups filtered water
	•	1 TBLS sea salt

Sneaky hormone disrupters🫧

	•	Candles - Phthalates are a group of chemicals that are used to make plastics more flexible and are often found in candles to help the fragrance last longer. They’ve been linked to interfering with the production and regulation of hormones. 

	•	Tap water - tap water contains pesticides, bleach, pharmaceuticals like antibiotics and birth control, heavy metals and so much more that wreak havoc in your body and on your hormones. 

	•	Receipts - Studies found that handling receipts can contain significant BPA that is 250 to 1,000x greater than the amount in a can of food. BPA can mimick the estrogen molecule tricking your body into thinking you have higher amounts of estrogen than you do. 

	•	Non stick cookware - The nonstick component is made up of Teflon, and Teflon contains a compound known as C8, which is harmful to both your health and the environment. According to a large body of research, C8 disrupts normal hormone function and lowers testosterone levels in men.

As a woman, your period is the best barometer of your health. It helps tell the story of your overall health status. It’s like a progress report of how you took care of your body the month prior. 

When your period arrives easily:
This is an A+ on your report card. When you have little to no pain, bloating, PMS, acne, or irregularities surrounding your bleed, this is a great sign of healthy hormones!

When your period is anything but easy:
Brutal cramps and PMS are your hormones' way of telling you they’re out of balance, and need more support.

It’s more than possible to balance your hormones naturally through simple lifestyle choices🍒

While your cycle is like a l vital sign for your health, another great barometer is your skin🐚

What you apply to your skin matters, BUT if you aren't building a foundation for good health.... skincare will only act as a band aid.

If you continue to suffer from acne and skin imbalances, it’s your body trying to tell you something. 

Common culprits of skin imbalances:

	•	Diet high in PUFA

So FIRST make sure you're consuming nourishing foods like fresh fruit, egg yolks, and liver (I take it as a supplement!). 

Prioritize protein from animal sources like raw milk, cheese, beef, eggs, yogurt, seafood, etc daily.

Focus on minerals like fresh in season fruit and fruit juices, seafood, quality sea salt, and bone broth. 

Avoid PUFAS like canola oil and other vegetable oils. Stick with grass fed butter, coconut oil, and avocado oil. I take vitamin E daily to help against the damage of these rancid oils. 

My favorite ways to lower stress are going for a walk in the sun, journaling, taking a social media break, and getting morning sun.

We’re still talkin best barometers for your health✨ Next up: digestion!

Digestion is a great check in point in your health because it is important for breaking down food into nutrients, which the body uses for energy, growth, and cell repair.

Signs of good digestion:
	•	Bowel movement 1-3x everyday
	•	Consistent energy
	•	Pain free bowel movements
	•	Don’t need a stimulant like coffee to have a bowel movement
	•	Healthy reactions to food

Signs your diegestion needs some help:
	•	Irregular bowel movements
	•	Constipation and/or loose stools
	•	Bloating
	•	Excessive gas/burping
	•	Painful digestion

How to support healthy digestion:
	•	Eat regularly every 3-4 hours to stabilize your blood sugar
	•	Avoid seed oils, processed, and fried foods
	•	Frequent movement like going on walks
	•	Prioritize quality animal protein like raw milk, grass fed beef, and pasture raised eggs
	•	Stay hydrated with minerals like coconut water, bone broth, and fresh fruit juices 
	•	Eat Dr. Ray Peat's carrot salad, cooked mushrooms, and/or bamboo daily

Another great natural check in point of your health is your sleep😴

Sleep is your body’s time to recover and heal. 

Hormonally speaking, progesterone and estrogen synthesize between the hours of 11pm - 2am, which means you need to be fast asleep during those hours. 

Those are also some of the hormones signaled by cortisol first thing in the morning— so if you don’t sleep well, the disruption of cortisol can disrupt the release of estrogen and progesterone.

This can also cause your thyroid and your metabolism to slow down, creating further problems. 

Signs of healthy sleep:
	•	7-9 hours of uninterrupted sleep
	•	Can fall asleep naturally in 15-20 minutes
	•	Steady energy throughout the day

Ways to improve sleep:
	•	Wear blue light blocking glasses after sundown
	•	Limit screen time 1 hour before bed
	•	Eat a bedtime snack 30 minutes - 1 hour before bed that involves protein
	•	Get sunlight first thing in the morning 
	•	Be active during the day
	•	Go to bed at a consistent time each night
	•	If your mind is racing, ‘brain dump’ in a journal beside your bed

What is prometabolic?
To put it simply, a pro-metabolic lifestyle is essentially eating, exercising, and living a lifestyle that supports the metabolism.

Your metabolism encompasses all chemical processes that keep you alive, including breathing, digestion, immune function, and cellular growth and repair.

It is literally responsible for EVERYTHING that happens in your body. It impacts your mood, energy levels, digestion, menstrual cycle, sex drive, fertility, sleep, and so much more. It not simply how we lose weight.

Good soup🥘

But really, I don’t know how to convince you how good this soup actually is, you just have to make it yourself. It is….🤌🏼

•4 cups chicken bone broth stock + 2 cups water
•1 cup uncooked wild rice
•8 ounces mushrooms
•4 cloves garlic
•2 medium carrots
•2 ribs celery
•1 large sweet potato
•1 onion
•1 bay leaf
•2 TBLSP Old Bay seasoning
•1 (14-ounce) can unsweetened coconut milk 
•2 chicken breasts, cooked and shredded
•2 large handfuls of kale
•Sea salt and pepper

	1.	Sauté the veggies. Heat (an extra) 1 tablespoon butter in a large pot over medium-high heat.  Add onion and sauté for 5 minutes, stirring occasionally, until soft and translucent.  Stir in the garlic and cook for an additional 1-2 minutes, stirring occasionally, until fragrant.
	2.	Add base ingredients: bone broth, wild rice, mushrooms, carrots, celery, sweet potato, bay leaf and Old Bay seasoning.  Stir to combine.
	3.	Continue cooking until the soup reaches a simmer.  Then reduce heat to medium-low, cover and simmer for 30 to 40 minutes until the rice is tender, stirring occasionally.
	4.	Add final ingredients: coconut milk and kale to the soup, and stir gently until combined. Taste and season with salt and pepper as needed.
	5.	Serve warm and enjoy!

Potato leek soup🥔

2 leeks + 1 onion
4 cloves garlic
4 cups chicken broth
Potatoes
1 tsp salt
1 tsp thyme
1 bay leaf
1 lb sausage

Cook the chopped leeks and onion in butter for 8-10 min, then add garlic and cook for another 1-2 minutes. Add the broth, potatoes, salt, bay leaf, and thyme. Bring to a boil then reduce heat and simmer covered for 20 minutes. Remove the bay leaf and blend the soup in stages until creamy. Cooke the sausage then add the creamed soup back into the pot. Top with a drizzle of olive oil, chives, and ground pepper before serving!
